Date:  	Sat, October 6, 2012 8:04 am &nbsp; &nbsp; (answered 9 October 2012)<br>
From:  	&quot;Anonymous&quot;<br>
Subject:  	Escaping AA<br>

<p>
Hello Orange,
<p>
My thoughts are a bit scattered at the moment so I apologize if this e-mail is
difficult to understand, but I just have to express my feeling and I believe you
might understand.  I am a 27 year old heroin addict with almost a year clean, save
for a few minor slips, and I feel as if AA is ripping me apart.  My home group is
incredibly liberal and open-minded.  There is no dogmatic preaching, no tirades
against other methods of recovery, no alienation of drug addicts.

<p>
People share openly about using therapy, meditation, maintenance drugs and whatever
other methods work for them.  Most members are successful professionals including a
quite famous cultural critic, professors, teachers, businessmen, etc, you get the
picture.  I think the permissive attitudes of this particular group and the sort of
open therapeutic dialogue it engenders have  caused me to stay here much longer than
other groups I have joined.  I have made friends with some incredibly intelligent,
radical free thinkers whom have made parts of the program work for them.

<p>
Over my years of attempting to achieve sobriety I have occasionally perused your
site, usually at a time when my faith in myself and AA is at a low point, and I
suppose that this is another one of those times.

<p>
I don't know what to do.

<p>
I feel so alienated, so lost, my cravings are so strong, and at some level I know
that the actual program of AA does not work, I understand how it draws people in,
manipulates them, utilizes all manner of cult recruiting techniques.

<p>
However, and this is a fairly significant however,

<p>
This group has helped me.  This group has given me intelligent and loving friends
who support me.  This group has been there for me on my off days, has helped me find
support for my other issues (trauma and a severe eating disorder resembling
anorexia).

<p>
I suppose I want to keep the baby and the bathwater, to remain connected to this
support group and social circle while giving mere lip service to the actual
foundations of the program.  This seems possible.  No one at this particular group
would judge me for this.  I have found the best of both worlds it seems, a social
and support structure based around abstinence from drugs and alcohol yet free of
traditional AA dogma and extremism.

<p>
I feel trapped.

<p>
This is due in part to my own life, my own mind, the ways that it plagues and
deceives and causes me to spiral into depression.  I can be unstable, I can be
social and active in life one day and then turn off my phone, lock myself in my
apartment, and isolate the next.

<p>
I love your website and the incredible depth of your critiques of AA, yet I feel
that I can retain myself and my mind and my own personal values while also remaining
active in this particular group and with this particular circle of people within it.

<p>
I suppose that this e-mail doesn't involve a single particular question or issue and
is more just me trying to express where I am now to someone who I feel could
understand and whose reply and opinion would be meaningful to me.

<p>
Feel free to publish this in your letters section but please remove my name if you
choose to do so.

<p>
Respectfully,<br>
Anonymous

<p>
<font color="blue">
Hello Anonymous,
<p>
Thank you for the letter. You sound quite sane and perceptive, and have stated your problem clearly.

<p>
I don't think that your problem is impossible to solve, or that you are trapped. And I think that you can
&quot;have your cake and eat it too&quot;.
<p>
<ol>
<li>
First off, don't burn your bridges behind you. You get moral support from your support group, so continue to
use it as long as it benefits you more than hurts you. There is nothing wrong with using the group, that is
what it is there for. Or is supposed to be for. You don't have to believe in Steppism. Just believe that
you want to feel better and be healthier and happier. If some of the people in the group give you comfort
and feelings of well-being, then associate with them.

<p>
Definitely check out the list of other recovery groups, here:
<a href="orange-alt_list.html" target="_blank">http://www.orange-papers.info/orange-alt_list.html</a>.
You might find another group of people who can also give you the moral support and companionship that you need.

<p><li>
Secondly, do you have a doctor who is helping you? I mean really helping. When you speak of your cravings
and depression and eating disorder and emotional cycling,
that tells me that you have untreated conditions that should be
treated by a good doctor or counselor, or both.
If you don't have such a doctor, please try to get one. Really.
There are lots of bad doctors, and mediocre doctors, and good doctors, so please get a good one.
If you already have a bad one, get a good one.

<p><li>
Dump the guilt and self-condemnation. And if you are practicing Steps Four through Seven, stop doing that.
You have already accurately assessed your situation, so you don't need to continue to beat up on yourself.
Here is where I part company with Steppers and say that the Steps do more harm than good.
It isn't your fault that you were born with some difficult medical conditions.
It isn't your fault that you were traumatized. It was pretty natural for you
to try using drugs to kill your pain. But now you have learned that heroin also causes more pain than
joy, so you are off of that. And of course you still crave the feel-good part of it. Of course you still want to
get a vacation from your pain and feel good. Don't feel guilty about that either. That is just natural.
Go read <a href="orange-addmonst.html" target="_blank">The Lizard-Brain Addiction Monster</a> for lots
more about that.

<p><li> Likewise, dump the self-condemnation and self-criticism in sharing. Just concentrate on how
you feel better now that you aren't killing yourself with heroin. Don't get into yammering about how bad you are
(or &quot;selfish&quot;, or &quot;manipulative&quot;, or &quot;dishonest&quot;, etc.),
not even if you are getting pressure from some people in the group to do so, and &quot;get really honest&quot;.
Read <a href="orange-us_stupid_drunks.html" target="_blank">The &quot;Us Stupid Drunks&quot; Conspiracy</a> for
more about that.
(By the way, those people who want to hear you wallowing in guilt and confessions are not your friends. They are
your mortal enemies. They will kill you while they enjoy watching you suffer.)

<p><li>
Also, stop calling yourself a heroin addict. That is the influence of Steppism again, where every time you
speak you have to say that you are an alcoholic or an addict.
You are not addicted to heroin any more, so you are no longer a heroin addict.
You may be an ex-addict, or you may be a person who is suffering from some mental conditions
that are causing you pain, but you are no longer a heroin addict. 

<p><li>
Learn how to stop driving yourself crazy. That is the title of a pamphlet by Dr. Hank Robb, who manages SMART
in Oregon. I wish I had a copy of it handy. I'll publish it if I find it.
SMART teaches a bunch of techniques for managing your own mind
and avoiding making things worse. It's easy to work yourself into a tizzy by concentrating on how bad things
are &#8212; &quot;awfulizing&quot;  &#8212;  complaining about how things are so awful.
Notice that you can make your mental pain worse, or minimize it, just by how you think
about it. If you think that it is really bad, really awful, and you can't stand it, then the pain
really is really awful and you can't stand it. On the other hand, if you think that it's bearable, and
you can get through it, and it isn't so bad, then it isn't so bad.
So again, check out some SMART meetings. If there are none in your city, you can get online and talk to
people in their forum or chat group. They are listed in the link above. Also, their web site has a bunch
of small documents in PDF format, and some of them may be very good reading for you.


<p><li>
Along the same lines, recognize that you are not trapped. You can go to A.A./N.A. meetings, or you can
not go, as you choose. There is no sense in getting to feeling all frantic and desperate and trapped when
you aren't in a trap.
There is no sense in working yourself up into a panic attack or anxiety attack.

<p><li>
So have a good day. Really. Concentrate on the good things. Count your blessings. Do some fun things.
Treat yourself to something good. Things will get better.
You have already kicked heroin, which is a huge victory. You have proven that you are strong and
powerful and a winner. You are winning. Congratulations. Now you can accomplish other things too.
</ol>

<p>
And if there is anything else that I can do to help, don't hesitate to write back.

<p>
Again, have a good day, and a good life.
<p>
== Orange
