<p>
I stumbled upon your page while doing some AA quote look-ups online.  Just a quick
question as I do not feel like reading further what I saw at a glance.

<p>
Are you basically an anti-AA site/crusader?  Or are you only trying to point out the
flaws in a program that has worked for many individuals?  The reasons why:

<p>
<ul>
<li>
1) Many people pick up multiple chips due to attending multiple meetings, while
others will pick only one and then not collect one at another, even though they
picked a white chip up at all of them.
<li>
2) I personally have turned in my chips over time, mainly to save the group from
having to buy more (I only picked up one white chip).  So if I picked up say 5 red
chips at various meetings, I turned them all in at my home group.  Therefore, my
home group did not have to buy more of those chips.  I have done this will all my
chips as I don't really care about chips myself.
<li>
3) Sometimes service type meetings (H&amp;I, etc.) have funds that they do not need for
any purpose.  In the past these groups have purchased things like chips and
schedules and let the members of those groups take them back to their home groups
for use.  This saves money for the home groups who send members to perform these
service tasks.
<li>
4) Like you also point out, milestone chips are often bought separately by sponsors,
friends, etc.  Therefore most of these I see do not come from a groups store of
chips, but instead are bought from a variety of places/AA Areas.
</ul>

<p>
All that being said, I do not claim to be perfect, I do not claim AA to be perfect.
What are you claiming?

<p>
Regards,

<p>
A sober man named Dan.

